<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> TTT: Combining Cultures/ Isengard<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 27, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
<br />
	Well, I&#8217;ve covered the first two minion cultures. Now let&#8217;s look at the big brutes of the Lotr game, the fighting Uruk-hai. They are not only the most popular minion culture now, but the biggest. <br />
<br />
Like the Raiders, the Uruk-hai from the Two Towers are broken down into groups. Generally, there are three main strategy groups besides the plain play Uruk-hai to kill strategy. Uruk-hai archers, Uruk-hai trackers, and Uruk-hai that function off site control.<br />
<br />
Let&#8217;s start with archers. Before the new set, there were only two Uruk-hai archers, Lurtz and Orthanc Assassin. Therefore, the strategy of archery with Uruks never existed until now. Ironically, these two minions happen to be more powerful than any of the new ones, so they will likely see some for those that will play Uruk-hai archery. What&#8217;s unique about the archer of Isengard? Well, machines for one. Another is their ability to exert to use semi-aimed archery. What? Does that mean Mr.Frodo over here can&#8217;t put on Isildur&#8217;s Bane and take burdens? Of course. What about Ring-bound decks? Well, their text is optional, so you can always use regular archery and save yourself some vitality. Machines can potentially rip into your opponent&#8217;s fellowship. The biggest problem they have to face is, of course, condition discard. I&#8217;ll introduce some potential solutions later.<br />
<br />
Now, one possible strategy with archers is someone I&#8217;m sure you all know. He happens to be the inventor of the Grima Bomb. Hmmm. Now who could that be? Yes, that&#8217;s right. Everyone probably recognizes friend Grima. While, Uruk-hai archers do well at dealing wounds, Grima specializes best at dealing exertions. There are many new Isengard conditions that are awful to your opponent. Leechcraft, while not having any hidden strategy, is just flat out good..or bad, depending on what side your on. Wounded is like a black breath that guarantees you at least one wound&#8230;and, unlike Black Breath, you don&#8217;t  even have to survive until the skirmish phase. Banished makes good use of that card by giving you a likely exhausted companion that can&#8217;t heal. Unferth, while not likely to see much play, is more than he seems. First off, he is an Isengard man, which lets you play those fun downgrading conditions. His ability to exert any companion or ally skirmishing an Isengard man is interesting. So, he is good early in the game when the fellowship is healthy as he is guaranteed an exertion by himself, two if accompanied by Grima. So what? They can assign them to an exhausted companion and be done with it. Maybe Saruman, Sote might be of assistance. If they exert to prevent an assignment, you&#8217;ve already dealt the exertion, so you&#8217;re opponent is faced with either taking exertions on a good companion&#8230;or taking exertions on a good companion AND taking more exertions. Hmmm..Ooops. Given, you have stripped companions of cards with Grima and have well placed conditions and common Saruman..gasp! Grima or Unferth may actually win their skirmishes..in which case they will have to take multiple exertions. Okay, sorry about that. I just have a soft spot for underused cards (those of you who have seen my attempts at Shire Countryside have an idea). <br />
<br />
The Uruk-hai trackers are unusual as none of them are damage +1, but all of them are fierce. This means that in these kind of decks we will be seeing probably less of Keeper of Isengard and more of other Sarumans. As you may notice, most of the Uruk-hai trackers are not high strength, thus you have to have some planning to make them work right. First off, some have low vitality, making them archery targets. While the 1 vitality ones can be expendable, you want to make the most of them by keeping them alive. Old cards like Spies of Saruman and new cards like Broad-bladed Sword help. Ok, they&#8217;ve made it past archery, but they are about to lose their skirmish. Add cards like Mauhur and Race Across the Mark (when combined with site control) and they&#8217;ve made it alive, but that still hasn&#8217;t done you any good. However, some can come back in a fierce skirmish, get more strength and even damage bonuses. This may seem like a lot of trouble to get a few wounds in, but it may yet be useful. Other trackers keep Just A Nuisance from becoming your nuisance and gives you an edge over the new discarding hobbits as well as giving you bonuses for defeating them. These tend to have higher strength than the others, giving you more possibilities for overwhelming and winning. The one last breed of trackers is the search Uruks (Ok, well Ugluk doesn&#8217;t really have a category except trackers, in general). There are only two of these, but they can be potent. While combined with Many Riddles, the searcher and seeker can almost guarantee a wound apiece maybe more. When the companion is finally exhausted, make use of it with a Tower of Orthanc or 4, forcing them to get rid of that companion&#8230;else give you a load of twilight. One thing you will need in tracker decks is condition discard. Why? Because if unbound hobbit decks are floating around, chances are you might run into Fearing the Worst. It tears apart this strategy right from the beginning. I suggest using either Black Traitor Saruman or Burning of Westfold, which, when combined with a bit of site control and played right, can keep the free peoples side condition free!<br />
<br />
Site control can be a powerful thing. The Uruk-hai have a few somewhat costly ways of gaining site control. The main way is the token method. Play Uruk-hai or wins skirmishes with Uruk-hai, then removing so many tokens to get a site. There are many Uruk-hai that play for less, get more strength, and gain special abilities like stacking when sites get under your control. Cards like Pillage of Rohan will keep your Uruk-hai safe from nasty events, most of which occur during the skirmish phase, thus making this card useful. This is also a possible remedy for the annoying Ring-bound men. Ranger Bows, Swordsman of Northern Kingdom an other nasty thorns get removed. Make your site 1 Western Emyn Muil (so long as you aren&#8217;t playing Ring-bound men yourself) and they&#8217;ve already got a problem to deal with. In addition, stacking Uruks is essentially like a better version of Goblin Swarms for your Uruks from which they play for less. <br />
<br />
<br />
Let&#8217;s see how the Isengard pairs with Dunland. Before I go into detail, though, I think I should address the issue of condition discard. Remember the problem I brought up before about Isengard machines and how prone they are to condition discard? Have other conditions that are the same way? Let&#8217;s look at them. Most free peoples condition discard cards require either Gandalf or Allies. Gandalf condition discards require a big sacrifice of either huge amounts of twilight or the loss of their own conditions&#8230;and the only real way to deal with that is&#8230;kill Gandalf, which is usually not that easy. Allies can be dealt with in a number of ways. Come Down, Dunlending Warrior, Dunlending Ravager, and even subtle cards like Rohan is Mine. The new Company of Archers is sure to come up and , since fellowship gets first archery action, this can become a problem. Maybe throw down a Covering Fire for your Uruk archers, at least, to protect your machines. <br />
<br />
Ok, now back to Dunland. As I had mentioned in my previous article on Dunland, possession discard can wreck a fellowship vs. an Uruk-hai deck simply because they will absolutely need possessions to win against those more powerful Uruks. Secret Folk, War Club, Wild Man Raid, Dunlending Pillager. The list goes on. Armor or Helm getting on your nerves? Win a skirmish and goodbye. This in combination with the Grima bomb is wicked. Now that may be pretty obvious so I&#8217;ll go a bit deeper. With the right cards, you can make any Dunland wan win a skirmish with the help of Rabble Rouser who can also deal extra exertion points which will certainly help the damage +1 Uruk-hai and you can still use Isengard cards like Leechcraft and Saruman&#8217;s Staff. The Staff is better used with common Saruman since he can assign himself, but that&#8217;s beyond the point. Hillman Horde gets you past archery if you control 2 sites (not hard with the combination of Dunland and Isengard working to get sites).Ravage the Defeated can be more devastating than a Grima bomb if used at the right time on the right companion. The Dunlending Madman, Robber, Wulf, and Band of Wild men are all or have the potential to be fierce. Now think about this in combination with Uruk-hai trackers who all happen to be fierce! Ouch. Ok, you lay out a huge assault squad of minions. They survive the onslaught with losing a companion or two, maybe more. Ok, now they are all fierce! Your opponent grumbles when two or three minions get assigned to Frodo on the second round. Even using normal minions with Savageries and War Cry of Dunland can be lethal. Ok, you survived round 1 ok, but can you survive #2 with an array of minions that are, not only, fierce, but majorly pumped up in strength as well? If they do, you can count on a severely damaged fellowship. Twilight a problem? Get down some heavy hitting Dunlanders who play minions post-skirmish and bam! You get a discount, archery immunity, and deal More damage than you originally were! Now there&#8217;s a load of damage +1 minion and they don&#8217;t have armor to help them out because you discarded it 2 turns ago. Stackers and No Refuge says &#8216;Goodbye&#8217; to choke and No Retreat, well&#8230;that speaks for itself. <br />
<br />
<br />
We find the fierce dilemma again with the Nazgul and Uruk trackers except they don&#8217;t have to win, necessarily. They fight them all&#8230;and then they fight them all, again. I find that when your opponent is faced with fierce skirmishes, they are already annoyed enough with having to assign them the first time, but when they assign the second time, they are very agitated and are more likely to make mistakes when assigning them. Carrying pumpers in your deck is way to mess up your opponent&#8217;s well thought out strategy. Nazguls also carries one of the best anti-archery cards, Wreathed In Shadow not only protects Nazgul, but Uruk-hai, and especially low vitality Dunland minions. It is not a possession, but it is less expensive than Hides as well. The downside. It is prone to discard and only affects unaimed archery. What about aimed archery? Pack Spies of Saruman or something&#8230;or&#8230;let them take the exertions. They can&#8217;t exert forever, and when they finally run out of vitality, it makes it that much easier to take them out. While most players will never combine Isengard with Nazgul save for Enquea, I believe it is quite overlooked. Nazgul take advantage of burdens and Isengard has interesting possibilities for burden adding. The Aragorn hate card is one, and they will not likely exhaust Aragorn with the new assigning abilities. What&#8217;s that? You can&#8217;t exert to prevent? Tssk.Tssk. Too bad. Beyond All Hope is expensive, but with Saruman&#8217;s Ambitions in fairly large quantities, it is not out of reach. It&#8217;s hard, but you could <br />
get it to work. Beyond Dark Mountains is a much less expensive card that can be equally damaging, especially if you kill the right guy. <br />
<br />
<br />
Sauron and Isengard, just like Orthanc and Barad-dur can be a strikingly good team. Archers are just as, if not, more effective with Sauron than the Raiders. While the Desert Lord and Hate combo is nice, but takes 2 turns and that&#8217;s only if they don&#8217;t heal. Sauron can deal exertions well, and the Uruk-hai archers deal out wounds. Orc Bowmen, Elite Crossbowmen and machines make the wounds skyrocket. Include at least one Enquea in your deck in case they do soak up burdens for even more fun. Once they have a pitfully wounded fellowship, take them out with Hates. Why not throw in Grima and play a Wounded on their man, make them soak up damage on him or her, then Hate them. Or better yet, why not just play it on a man that is exhausted (or one wound away from exhaustion since it already deals an exertion), then Hate them that same turn. Hard to set up, but worth the effort&#8230;or use Banished to force a confrontation, and, if it doesn&#8217;t happen, take him out with Hate. In addition, Sauron gives you better option for condition discard. Volley Fire may seem pointless, but if all your archers are exerted (thus being unable to add to archery total) and will die to your opponent&#8217;s archery or skirmishes anyway, you may as well get some use out of it and an exhausted companion is nothing to grumble at. Even more opportunities for Hate. The best way to play the Hate combo, though, is in one turn. You would, then, need exertions or wounds during or before the maneuver phase. One of You Must Do This is great for mixed race fellowship in case people still play it. No Dawn For Men is better, though, because it doesn&#8217;t rely on mixed fellowship and you get to choose where the exertions go provided you control sites. With even one, though, you can set up a companion kill during the manuever if they have 3 or less remaining vitality. Wounded deals an exertion, No Dawn For Men deals an exertion, Hate deals the final blow, then they have one less companion to fight when the skirmish phase finally arrives. It may seem like a difficult combo to pull off, but remember that most of the time you may not even need it to kill off companions as you will already be dealing wounds. <br />
<br />
Moria and Isengard present some interesting new concepts. Runners obviously are aid Isengard in the twilight area, but actually, two towers has introduced the ability to swarm with Isengard, as well. Foot Soldiers, Plains Runners, Orthanc Warriors and so on, all play for cheap and have the potential to deal severe damage, as well. Throw in some ally killers like Dunlending Warrior and those cheap Uruk Raiders become monsters. All in all, a team of Moria and Isengard can create swarm with a twist. If you can manage to get more minions than companions down, you can keep your Foot Soldiers and other minions like him alive long enough to deal some damage&#8230;or you can just keep them safe with cards like Get Back. While they don&#8217;t add to the swarm, they do fight their second time and much harder than their first one. Mauhur is a good choice as well. Fairly cheap, fierce minion than can keep those weak dudes alive to make a comeback. Using strategy, you can use the assignment benefit from tracker cards to set up your swarm the way you want it. <br />
<br />
<br />
Lastly, we have the Raiders culture. The best combos here that I can think of is Uruk-hai archers combined with Raider archery. Use the token cards like Arrow From the South to double the opposing fellowship over with exertions after exerting and healing, then take them out with your Uruk-hai archers and machines. Large fellowships can be taken care of by simply throwing an Enquea or two into the mix. He also may help if your opponent starts abusing Isildur&#8217;s Bane as a remedy for losing companions...in any case they can only substitute a maximum of 4 wounds as burdens. Why not include a few burden cards just to throw them off balance. You can, however, prevent this by simply exerting all your archers down. If you can find room for Grimas or Unferth (He&#8217;s not terrible, remember) in your deck, than Wounded can be huge. Wounded=1 exertion + Desert Lord=2 exertions=exhausted Aragorn, Faramir, Eomer, etc&#8230;that can&#8217;t heal! That leaves your opponent with a rather undesirable choice&#8230;to kill off a key main or to let the rest of your companions die. In addition, that increases your options. Let loose an Orthanc Champion or assign with common Saruman and they can&#8217;t do a thing about it. Once you start dishing out the wounds, you can use Saruman, Sote to essentially kill the companions of your choice. From there, winning will be nearly certain. <br />
<br />
<br />
Well, that wraps up the minion cultures. In the next and last article, I will look into the free peoples possibilities. Until then&#8230;<br />
<br />
<br />
